                            <origDate>
                                <date calendar="Śaka">9th</date>
                                <date calendar="Julian" notBefore="0875" notAfter="0975">9th-10th</date>
                            </origDate>
                        </origin>
                    <provenance type="found" notAfter="1909">
                        <ab>The <quote>énigmatique dalle</quote> on which this inscription is engraved was found at the <quote>petite pagode</quote> near the <quote>vestiges à Tĩnh Yên</quote> first reported in <bibl><ptr target="cic-bibl:parmentier-1909"/>: <biblScope>285</biblScope></bibl>, which must be identifiable with the shrine <placeName xml:id="findspot" type="modern" ref="cic-geo:mieu-thang-gu">Miếu Thằng Gù</placeName> that we visited on <date when="20111126"/>. Its general shape, and particularly its lotus ornament, were described, with drawings in side and top view, in <bibl><ptr target="cic-bibl:parmentier-1918"/>: <biblScope>243</biblScope>, fig. 247</bibl>. In neither of these publications does Parmentier mention the inscription.
                        </ab>
                    </provenance>
                        <provenance type="observed" notBefore="1942">
                            <ab>The existence of the inscription was first mentioned in the second supplement to the inventory of Campā inscriptions published in 1942 (<ptr target="cic-bibl:coedes-1937-1966"/>, vol. II, p. 208), where the type of object was wrongly stated to be a socle, and the language of the inscription was misidentified as Sanskrit.</ab>
                        </provenance>
                       <provenance type="observed" notBefore="2011">
                           <ab>We found the slab behind the building of the Bảo Tàng Văn Hóa Sa Huỳnh-Champa Duy Xuyên (Duy Xuyên Museum of Sa Huỳnh-Champa Culture) on <date when="20111114"/>, and were able to identify it as <ptr target="#inv-general"/> a few days later. It then bore no local inventory number. We were informed on <date when="20111123"/> that the object had been found by a Mr. Thân Vinh Lộc in the <placeName type="modern" ref="cic-geo:mieu-thang-gu">Miếu Thằng Gù</placeName>.</ab> 
                        </provenance>
